Why isn't the Fed doing its job?
STANFORD – The nomination of new board members for the US central bank, the Federal Reserve, gives Americans – and the US Congress – the opportunity to reflect on the world's most important central bank and its future path.
The obvious question that must be asked first is how it was possible that the Fed failed so dramatically in its most important mandate – ensuring price stability.
The fact that the Fed was completely taken aback by current inflation suggests a fundamental failure.
Clearly, institutional soul-searching is now called for.
But while monetary policy makes headlines, the Fed is now primarily significant as a financial regulator.
A further big question is therefore whether it will use its enormous power to advance climate or social policy.
The Fed could, for example, refuse credit to companies in the fossil fuel sector; it could require banks to only extend credit to companies with certified net-zero emission plans or steer lending towards desired alternatives.
In addition, it could decide to explicitly take regulation in the name of equality or ethnic justice, by instructing banks where and to whom loans should be granted, who should be hired and who fired, etc.
But before we turn to the question of which direction Fed regulation will move or should move, it is first necessary to clarify the Fed's grave failure.
In 2008, the US government made a consequential decision: Financial institutions could continue to obtain funds for risky investments primarily through the sale of short-term, run-sensitive debt instruments, but armies of new regulatory agencies would henceforth evaluate the risk sensitivity of the institution's assets.
The hope was that the regulatory agencies would no longer overlook large chunks like the subprime mortgages on bank balance sheets.
Over the following ten years of more detailed regulation and regular scenario-based "stress tests," the Fed's regulatory army never once questioned what would happen in the case of a pandemic.
When the pandemic then actually hit in early 2020, the Fed abandoned its "never again" promises from 2008 and intervened on an even larger scale.
In March, the commercial banks proved themselves unable to act as intermediaries in the market for ordinary US Treasury securities.
Daher stützte die Fed den Markt.
Kritiker hatten lange auf die Probleme mit den Liquiditätsregeln der Fed hingewiesen. Die Korrekturen auf den Märkten wären einfach gewesen, aber naheliegende Reformen hatte man auf die lange Bank geschoben.
Später kam es zu einem Run auf Geldmarktfonds.
Die Fed rettete die Geldmarktfonds erneut.
Nichts ist einfacher zu beheben als Runs auf dem Geldmarkt, aber dazu kam es nie.
Moreover, the Fed also financed the issuance of new municipal bonds and supported corporate bond prices by essentially providing a guarantee à la "whatever it takes."
In 2008, the Fed and the US Department of the Treasury had fought against the idea of raising the market price of all mortgages as part of the financial industry rescue package - the Troubled Assets Relief Program.
But in 2020, with the "Powell put" and other measures, a clear floor for corporate bond prices had been established.
The predictable rebuttal to this criticism will be: So what?
The lockdowns due to Covid-19 could have triggered a financial crisis.
<s>The flood of rescue measures has worked so well that our problem today is inflation.
<s>We need not worry about systemic risks because the Fed and the US Treasury Department will simply extinguish any new fire with another flood of money.
<s>Of course, the problem lies in the incentives these strategies have created.
<s>Why bother making efforts to use emergency funds or balance room for buying at falling prices, providing liquidity, or treating a "fire sale" as a "buying opportunity"?
<s>The Fed will always overtake everyone and reap the profits.
<s>Why issue stocks when you can simply take on a loan, knowing that the state will support the debt or help the company out of trouble, as was the case with airlines?
<s>Why hesitate as an investor when buying dubious papers, if their value in bad times is guaranteed by another "whatever-it-takes promise" from the Fed?
<s>No wonder America is drowning in debt.
<s>Everyone assumes that taxpayers will absorb the losses during the next downturn.
<s>Student loans, state pensions, and mortgages pile up, waiting for their turn in Uncle Sam's rescue operation.
But every new crisis requires even more transfusions.
Bondholders will eventually refuse to pour more money into rescue operations, and people won't be happy with trillions of newly printed money.
If the expected rescue packages do not materialize, we will wake up in a great conflagration—and the firefighters will be burned out.
In 2008, regulators and lawmakers at least recognized the moral hazard and worried that investors would pocket gains in good times while taxpayers would bear the losses in bad times.
In 2020, the focus was only on self-congratulation about the rescue actions.
The Fed, which in 2008 failed to see the risks of subprime mortgages just as it failed to anticipate the pandemic in 2020 and now intends to conduct stress tests in light of "climate risks," will, without a doubt, also overlook the next war, the next pandemic, the next state bankruptcy, or any other disruptive event.
The Fed regulators do not even ask about the aforementioned events.
Although there are endless discussions about "interconnections," "strategic interactions," "network effects," and "credit cycles," it has not been possible to define "systemic" risk, apart from turning it into a catchall phrase that grants regulators sweeping powers.
Regulatory agencies will never be able to predict risks, precisely measure the assets of financial institutions, or ensure that enormous debts can always be paid off.
We must reverse the basic premise of a financial system where the state stands ready to pay off mountains of debt in bad times. And we must do this before the fire department is tested.
<s>A better regulation can bridge partisan divides.
The Left is right when it argues that the big banks are inefficient oligopolies that benefit most Americans very little.
However, it gets the root cause wrong.
A massive effort to comply with regulations is a major obstacle to entry into the market.
The call for "more" regulation is pointless.
Regulatory provisions are either smart or dumb, effective or ineffective, full of unwanted consequences or well-conceived.
We need better regulation.
We need more capital, not thousands of pages of regulations.
Capital provides a buffer against all shocks and requires regulators to have no prophetic abilities.
The Fed shamefully stopped companies in the Narrow Banking and payment services sectors, which could contribute to meeting the financial needs of many people in America.
Before the Fed devotes itself to saving the planet and making amends for injustices, it should be held accountable for how poorly it fulfills its fundamental task of protecting the financial system.
